ChatGPT said:
When you open the modal using AJAX ($("#waitinglistmodal").modal("show");), the issue with the close button (data-dismiss="modal") not working is likely due to one of these reasons:

Possible Issues and Fixes
1. Ensure jQuery and Bootstrap JS are Loaded
Make sure jQuery and Bootstrap JavaScript are included in your project and are not loaded multiple times, as this can cause conflicts.

2. Check for Missing Bootstrap Data Attributes
Since you are opening the modal via AJAX, you don’t need data-toggle="modal" on the button. Instead, just ensure you trigger it correctly using JavaScript.

3. Handle Dynamic Content
When opening the modal dynamically, Bootstrap might not properly initialize the modal's backdrop and event handlers. Try manually handling this:

$(".assignbtn").click(function () {
    let modal = $("#waitinglistmodal");

    // Ensure Bootstrap initializes it properly
    modal.modal({
        backdrop: 'static', // Ensure the backdrop works
        keyboard: true      // Enable keyboard close (ESC key)
    });

    modal.modal("show");

    // Ensure close buttons work
    modal.find("[data-dismiss='modal']").off("click").on("click", function () {
        modal.modal("hide");
    });
});
4. Ensure Bootstrap Event Handling
You can also listen for Bootstrap’s modal events to make sure it's correctly initialized:

$('#waitinglistmodal').on('shown.bs.modal', function () {
    console.log("Modal is opened");
});

$('#waitinglistmodal').on('hidden.bs.modal', function () {
    console.log("Modal is closed");
});
5. Manually Remove Modal Elements on Close
If the modal does not close properly after being opened via AJAX, you can manually remove its backdrop and hide it:

$(".assignbtn").click(function () {
    let modal = $("#waitinglistmodal");
    
    modal.modal("show");

    modal.on("hidden.bs.modal", function () {
        modal.removeClass("show");
        $(".modal-backdrop").remove();
    });
});
